How to use course-omatic

 About

Course-omatic is a design tool for creating course designs. It provides an interface for creating storyboards with all the units and activities (including assessments) for a course, as well as basic course information like goals, learning outcomes, and a description. It provides various statistics and summaries as you go that help to understand the big picture in terms of how a student might experience the course. It can save a design for re-use or sharing, and it can produce static reports.


It is designed to support a learning design process derived from ABC-LD (ABC Learning Design), augmented slightly to meet the needs of self-paced online learning (though it will still work just fine for the standard process) . ABC-LD is an agile approach to building courses that has been fully tried and tested in institutions and organizations globally. This tool currently only supports the creation of storyboards. Later I might add support for more parts of the process.


It does not need a back-end server to run (which means it can be displayed inside a learning management system or any other system that allows HTML files to be displayed) but, in order to achieve this, a few compromises have had to be made. The only way to share this is either in-person/via a meeting app, or by saving a course and sharing the saved file. In either case only one person can work on it at a time.


If you find any bugs (there are some) or want any changes to the features or way that it works, contact me, Jon Dron.


The process for creating a course is roughly as follows:

When you first open the page it will present you with a blank course for editing...


Edit the course information


Start with the "Edit course information" button and fill in the details. It is a good idea to add the learning outcomes at this point but you can add and change them later as needed.


As you make changes, course-omatic will save what you have entered (to your own local disk) so don't worry too much if you are interrupted or have to refresh the page - the details of anything you have saved should normally be intact. You can also explicitly save versions (more on that soon) which I highly recommend you should do now and then. The app is not super-reliable and it is easy to lose your work. You will also need to do this if you use a different browser, switch to a different machine, or want to share it with someone else.


Beware that, when you add a learning outcome, it appears at the bottom of the list so, if a few are already entered, you may need to scroll down to find them. Try not to leave any blank - you can get rid of ones you don't want using the x button next to the outcome. You cannot reorder the outcomes, sorry: if that feature is desired by enough people, I should be able to add it. I just figured it was more work than needed when you can simply copy and paste between them


Notice how the details appear on the page when you save the form.


Make some units

Next, click "Create new unit" and fill in the details. This creates a panel for the unit into which you will soon add some activities. Do this for as many units as you think you will need. Again, you can change this later, and add more whenever you want. There are buttons to delete and edit units on each unit panel.



Notice how units are added below the course information panel. You can scroll down to find them all: they may not immediately be visible.


The fun part: add activities


Next, add the learning activities. This is where it starts to get interesting.



You can add 8 different broad categories of learning activity. These are based on those used in the ABC-Learning Design model, with the addition of two more that we think are important, especially for self-paced learners: reflection (such as learning diaries and surveys) and cooperation (doing something on your own that also helps other people). These activity types are very useful as your course starts to grow because you or anyone else can quickly get a sense of the pedagogical shape of a course, and to avoid unintentionally letting one kind of activity dominate (unless you want it that way). It is also really handy for thinking about what an activity really entails - what you might think of as a single activity might well actually be comprised of several different types. For example, you might think of an exam as something that takes 3 hours but it actually takes many times longer for most students because, in real life, students will spend an average of 25% of the total course time (typically around 30 hours for a 3-credit course) on revision. If they lack experience then, left to their own devices, this might consist of nothing but repeated acquisition but this is an opportunity for you to incorporate different and more effective active revision strategies in your storyboard: for instance, practice, discussion, or collaboration might be very helpful. Having done all of that then, if those activities happen to provide good evidence of successful learning, then you might eventually choose not to use an exam at all!


If you are not sure which to use, pass your mouse over the key: it will provide some examples. You can find more in-depth explanations of each of the activity types and how to select appropriate types at abc-ld.org.  Here is a very brief reference, from https://magazines-static.raspberrypi.org/issues/full_pdfs/000/000/458/original/HelloWorld_14_digital.pdf?1602836751 (p.74, if you want to read the article):


This is what the form looks like:




As you add activities you will be asked for information about them, including whether they are assessed (in which case you will get some more options), how long you expect students to spend on them (if you are unsure, there's a link to a handy calculator at the top right of the screen) which unit to add them to, and what specific type of activity you want them to do. You can add you own if what you want is not available on the list. You can also select which course outcomes the activity addresses.


You can select a specific activity from a pre-made list or, if you wish, add a new one by selecting "Add New..." from the list.


You can enter anticipated study time in HH:MM  (or H:MM or HH:M) format if you wish or, if you enter a number of minutes, courseomatic will calculate the hours and minutes for you.


If you select the "assessed" checkbox, you will get some more options.





This is useful information for when you need to fill in marking scheme forms and helps you to keep a track of how much time you are committing to marking.


Notice how the course information is updated when you save the activity.


The activities will appear as "cards" in whatever unit you have selected.


 You can drag activity cards around, including to other units, or you can set the unit manually by editing the card. Dragging can be a little unreliable - make sure that a gap opens up where you intend to drag the card before dropping it. There are also arrow buttons for moving them around, which can be easier at times.


There are three other buttons: edit (does what it says), clone (makes a copy) and delete (does what it says, but not before checking you mean it).


Assessed activities are displayed with a special star in the top right of the card. To see or change the full content, click the Edit button.


The clone button is really useful for adding activities that are common to each unit, such as reading - it is much easier to edit the clone than to fill in all the details from scratch. You can drag clones to other units.


As you add activities and fill in their details, course-omatic will automatically calculate the study hours per unit and across the course, it will display a pie chart of the relative amounts of time students are expected to spend for each activity type, and it will tell you which activities are assessed, which outcomes have yet to be assessed, and some other useful information. A bit more information is shown in the HTML export report.



Saving, loading, and producing reports


You can save or load a course using the save/load button. This also provides options to save reports as PDF, to the clipboard, or in HTML format. HTML format is usually the best. It will create a single HTML page containing (hopefully) all the information you have entered and some calculated data about the course. This provides a bit more detail than the view in the editor. You can share this with others, or use it as a reference when writing the course itself. The files are shared wherever your browser normally shares its files.




Calculating study hours

The link at the top right of the page will display another form. You can fill in as much or as little as you need for this. It provides a simple way to calculate reading time, writing time, revision time, coding time, and time for various other common activities. It's a bit rough and ready but it can be handy for getting rough estimates. Just copy the times back onto your activity form as needed.
